ce:section.ce:para:
A novel immunostimulatory nanocomposite vaccine was rationally designed by self-assembling engineered virus-like particles (VLP) encapsulating oligonucleotide CpG-gold nanoparticle conjugates (CpG-Au@HBc VLP) through electrostatic interactions. The use of AuNPs generated enhanced immunogenicity of CpG and VLPs on both humoral and cellular immune pathways, suggesting that CpG-Au@HBc VLP nanocomposite could induce robust cellular and humoral immune response, making it a potential vaccine for future prophylactic and therapeutic application [105]. Seok et al. [106] developed an intradermal pH1N1 DNA vaccine delivery platform using microneedles (MNs) coated with a polyplex-containing poly lactic-co-glycolic acid/polyethyleneimine (PLGA/PEI) NPs that rapidly dissolved in porcine skin and induced a greater humoral immune response than that of intramuscular polyplex delivery or naked pH1N1 DNA vaccine delivery by a dry-coated MN. As shown in Fig. 14.7
                  , the red fluorescence markedly disappeared within 5min, indicating that insertion of the polyplex-coated MN into skin led to rapid dissolution of the polyplexes from the MN surface. Cryosections of the vaccination site confirmed distribution of fluorescent dye-labeled polyplexes in the skin (Fig. 14.8
                  ), where they should interact with the immune cells [106].
